            </tr>
    <tr><th>total:</th><td class="right">7737</td><td> </td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>


<h4>Descriptive Status</h4>
<p>
    The <a href="https://glottolog.org/glossary#sec-descriptivestatusofalanguage">descriptive
    status</a> of a language measures how extensive a grammatical
    description there exists for a language.
</p>

<p>
    For the purpose of the descriptive status Glottolog's regular document types are
    mapped
    a more coarse grained <b>M</b>ost <b>E</b>xtensive <b>Description</b> (MED) type as
    follows:
</p>

<table class="table table-nonfluid">
    <thead>
    <tr>
        <th>MED type</th>
        <th>Description</th>
        <th># of languages</th>
        <th>% of languages</th>
    </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
            <tr>
                <th>long grammar</th>
                <td>Grammar with more than 300 pages</td>
                <td class="right">1892</td>
                <td class="right">24.01%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <th>grammar</th>
                <td>Grammar with less than 300 pages</td>
                <td class="right">1034</td>
                <td class="right">13.12%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <th>grammar sketch</th>
                <td>Grammar sketch</td>
                <td class="right">1955</td>
                <td class="right">24.81%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <th>phonology/text</th>
                <td>New Testament, Text, Phonology, (typological) Study Of A Specific Feature or Dictionary</td>
                <td class="right">1056</td>
                <td class="right">13.40%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <th>Wordlist or less</th>
                <td>Wordlist or less</td>
                <td class="right">1944</td>
                <td class="right">24.67%</td>
            </tr>
    <tr><th>total:</th><td> </td><td class="right">7881</td><td> </td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>


